A New Science
In this summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to ponder the necessity of a new science that could be as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists assume that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
Considering the great challenges, it is believed that there is only little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: Firstly, the great unsolved puzzles of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), which require enormous investments and infrastructure of the First World to explore. Secondly, data acquisition, meaning work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solutions must be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Furthermore, many believe that the only difficult part of the work would be to use already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could deny that?
The models of today do work.
However, an increasing group of scientists points out phenomena that are not well explained by today's theories.
Although these problems arise more frequently, they are also skillfully sidestepped because there simply is no science with which to explain these problems.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
The knowledge in individual scientific disciplines is fairly well-established.
At least the part of physics that we as ordinary people encounter is well-researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – while there are still a few things in our bodies that we don't understand, it is assumed that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
Additionally, there are the new social sciences that focus on people and societies.
In each of these areas – Physics, Biochemistry, and Social Sciences – the theories are firmly established and mostly also stand without dispute.
Each discipline has its own language and mechanisms.
In very rare cases is a scientist an expert in more than one field because these worlds and languages are fundamentally different.
This means that we cannot find an answer to complex questions that require the inclusion of several disciplines.
For example, think of the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction occurs on the basis of physics. The information conveyed through this interaction is transmitted due to the laws of electricity.
Furthermore, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate by exchanging chemical substances and also transmit information in this process.
In the interaction between two brains, a new level is added: Here, information exchange takes place via language, signs, and concepts.
At each level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes at each level.
Information is exchanged between these levels as well, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this deficiency, some scientists have tried to redefine the toolset for explaining phenomena at one level, in order to then apply it at another level.
These efforts then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanatory patterns works well, but the fundamental problem is not solved: What is the nature of the information exchanged between these levels and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in every case, there is this embarrassing lack of knowledge about how the entire system functions.
The interdisciplinary group of scientists who met in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science".
The researchers come from various countries and disciplines and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
Besides scientists from the relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, linguists, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discourse.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy", where scientific foundations from one level are adapted and expanded for application to another.
Others, however, believe that a completely new approach is required.
From your perspective, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents, and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches will emerge through scientists who currently do not have access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Unrestricted thinking is an underestimated factor.
Nearly all activities that take place under the banner of "science," like their counterparts in the world of business, have developed an institutional character.
It is believed that developing countries need to build similar resources as industrial countries. However, this could stifle creative thinking.
Viele junge Wissenschaftler erleben derzeit eine Revolution, und viele dieser – manchmal revolutionären – Ideen stammen aus Laboratorien und Forschungszentren, die nicht mit den großen Institutionen in Zusammenhang stehen.
Die durchdachtesten Ansätze im Bereich mathematischer Algorithmen kamen zwanzig Jahre lang aus der Sowjetunion, wo es an allen Ecken und Enden an Rechnerkapazitäten mangelte.
Die genialsten und im wahrsten Sinne des Wortes weltbewegenden Erkenntnisse im Bereich Physik der letzten Jahrzehnte kamen nicht wie erwartet aus den bekannten Innovationszentren, sondern aus Budapest.
In Iran gibt es eine Tradition der Architektur, die Kognitionswissenschaftlern zu wichtigen Erkenntnissen verhalf.
Und die radikalsten neuen Ideen im Bereich der zweiten Generation künstlicher Intelligenz (die so genannten „autonomen Agenten“) stammen heute aus Prag.
The most creative scientific achievements have entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, it changed the identity of space and time. The FIS Conference in July was the unexpected start of an attempt to redefine the universe in this manner.
Those gaps were identified for which explanations must be found.
More scientists from innovative regions will be included in this group to then identify the problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or discovered, if you prefer.

